    <title>Combined summary - Proposed BIP for OP_CAT</title>
    <updated>2023-10-30T10:09:02.939427+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2023-October/022101.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>A draft BIP has been proposed to activate the OP_CAT opcode as a Tapscript opcode. The BIP provides detailed specifications for implementing OP_CAT, which aims to address the lack of a general purpose way to concatenate values on the stack in Bitcoin tapscript. By enforcing a maximum stack element size of 520 Bytes, Tapscript overcomes previous concerns about memory usage, making OP_CAT feasible. The benefits of OP_CAT include simplifying multi-signature schemes, enabling more efficient script construction, and expanding the functionality of Bitcoin tapscript. To prevent misuse, the draft BIP proposes various mitigations and encourages feedback from the community before formal submission. The email also mentions that discussions about Bitcoin Script often lead to the desire for CAT and explains why adding additional opcodes would be controversial. The sender expresses gratitude to Ethan for writing up the BIP and provides contact information for Andrew Poelstra. Additionally, the email includes a link to an article on multisig using tree signatures and mentions the use of Proton Mail secure email.</summary>
